{"title_page": "Paul Brickhill", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Paul Brickhill\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = Paul Chester Jerome Brickhill\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1916|12|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1991|04|23|1916|12|20|df=y}} \n| death_place      = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = \n| language         = \n| residence        = \n| nationality      = \n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| home_town        = \n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = ''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]''<br /> ''[[The Dam Busters (book)|The Dam Busters]]''<br /> ''[[Reach for The Sky (book)|Reach for The Sky]]''\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc.; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Paul Chester Jerome Brickhill''' (20 December 1916{{spaced ndash}}23 April 1991) was an Australian fighter pilot, prisoner of war, and author who wrote ''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]'', ''[[The Dam Busters (book)|The Dam Busters]]'', and ''Reach for the Sky''.\n\n==Early life==\nBrickhill was born in [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] to [[journalist]] George Russell Brickhill (1879\u20131964) and Izitella Victoria Brickhill (nee Bradshaw).<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 17 & 19.</ref> He was the third son of the couple's five children, the others being Russell (1911\u20132002), Ayde Geoffrey (1914\u2013 ), Lloyd (1918\u20132011), and Clive (1923\u20132009).<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 21, 24 & 26.</ref> When Brickhill was 11 the family moved to Sydney where he was educated at [[North Sydney Boys High School]]. A classmate, and friend, was actor [[Peter Finch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/north-shore/his-great-escape-how-famous-author-paul-brickhill-ended-his-days-in-a-small-sydney-flat/news-story/8c2af4c28654cf56bc535d18b68ea3d0|title=Great Escape author\u2019s mystery life|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nBrickhill left school in 1931 as his father had been made redundant by the Depression. While his other brothers continued with their education it was necessary for Brickhill, who was regarded as the least academic of the children, to get a job to assist his older brother Russell in bringing money into the family.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 37.</ref> He was sacked from his first two jobs due to his stutter. He then got a job as office boy and then lift boy at the Adelaide Steamship Company. That job did not last long, as Peter Finch, who was by now working as a copy boy, was able to convince a news editor at ''[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]]''  to interview Brickhill in 1932.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 39.</ref> Brickhill was hired as a copy boy, and within a year promoted to cadet journalist. Within a few years he had worked his way up to journalist, and by 1940 was a sub-editor.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 47.</ref>\n\n==World War II==\nBrickhill was initially unimpressed by war fever, until the shock of the invasion of France and subsequent withdrawal from Dunkirk, coupled with boredom with his deskbound sub-editor job, caused him to enlist on 6 January 1941 with the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] (RAAF).<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 49.</ref>\nHis flight training commenced in March 1941 at the Number 8 Elementary Flying Training School at Narrandera, New South Wales as undertaken in Australia \nUnder the [[British Commonwealth Air Training Plan|Empire Air Training Scheme]]. Brickhill undertook advanced training as a [[Fighter aircraft|fighter]] pilot in Canada and the United Kingdom before being assigned to [[No. 92 Squadron RAF]], a unit equipped with [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]]s and part of the [[Desert Air Force]] in North Africa. \n\nOn 17 March 1943, he was shot down over [[Tunisia]] and became a [[prisoner of war]].<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 1 to 12.</ref> He was flown to Italy on 23 March, then sent by train to Germany. After initially being held at the [[Dulag Luft]] at [[Oberursel (Taunus) | Oberursel]], a central receiving and interrogation station for captured enemy airman for the [[Luftwaffe]], he was sent to [[Stalag Luft III]], in [[Lower Silesia]], 150 km southeast of Berlin, arriving there on 4 April 1943.<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 84 to 85.</ref>\nBrickhill became involved with organizing the camp's escape, initially as a lookout or \"stoogie\", before volunteering to work as a digger on the \"Tom\" tunnel\".<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 102 to 105.</ref> He developed [[claustrophobia]], and as a result was eventually reassigned and put in charge of security for the forgers. Because of his claustrophobia and the risk that he would panic and block the escape of others behind him, he was not allowed to take part in the [[Stalag Luft III escape|mass escape attempt]], which is today known as \"The Great Escape\".<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 124.</ref>\n\nFollowing the announcement of the murder of the escapees who had been recaptured following the Great Escape, Brickhill became determined to document the event. Discussing the subject with fellow prisoner Conrad Norton, they identified that many of their fellow prisoners had other tales of daring escapes, and that they could provide the possibility of publishing a book following the end of the war. As Brickhill had been involved in \"The Great Escape\", he concentrated on that story, while Norton collected individual tales.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 138.</ref> As prisoners were forbidden from writing anything other than letters and postcards, they collected every piece of paper they could find and, writing in as small a hand as possible, they collected stories and hid them from the guards. \n\nOn [[D-Day]], while still in captivity, Brickhill heard on German radio of two huge Allied armadas heading towards [[Cap d'Antifer]] and [[Calais]].  These were diversions created by [[No. 617 Squadron RAF]] to fool the Germans, however, a fact he learned months later.\n\n==Return to journalism==\n\nFollowing the end of the war, while the terms of his enlistment with the RAAF had been that he had to serve for 12 months following the cessation of hostilities, Brickhill was granted six months' leave without pay. During his leave he returned to journalism, working as a London-based correspondent for [[Associated Newspapers]]. Meanwhile outside of working hours he had typed up his and Norton's stories and selected David Higham as their literary agent.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 162.</ref> With Higham's help the manuscript was accepted by [[Faber & Faber]] and published as ''Escape to Danger'' in 1946.\n\nAfter working for Associated Newspapers for a period, Brickhill returned to Australia, taking a job as a sub-editor at ''[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]]'' newspaper in Sydney, Australia.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 194.</ref>\n\nBrickhill and Norton had agreed that each would retain the copyright to the chapters that they had written for ''Escape to Danger''. As a result while awaiting for sufficient stocks of paper to be obtained to print the book, Brickhill was able to sell a condensed version of his chapter on the Great Escape to several newspapers in Australia.\n\n==The Great Escape and The Dam Busters==\nAfter the end of World War II, John Nerney, head of the [[Air Historical Branch]] of the [[British Air Ministry]] identified the need for a history of 617 Squadron. While trying to find a suitable author he discussed the issue with [[John Pudney]], who was an editor at ''[[News Review]]''. Pudney had liked ''Escape to Danger'' and suggested that Brickhill be considered.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 196.</ref>\n\nFollowing up Pudney's recommendation, Nerney approached Brickhill in February 1949, who jumped at the offer. While doing all it could to assist his research the Air Ministry could only provide Brickhill with a small honorarium, and no guarantee of publication other than as a government produced publication.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 197.</ref> In an attempt to obtain an advance which would pay enough for him to leave his current job as a sub-editor at ''[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]]'' and relocate to England Brickhill approached a number of Australian publishers to see if they were interested in an Australian edition of the book. None was interested so Brickhill was forced to decline Nerney's offer.<ref name=Dando-CollinsP198>Dando-Collins. Page 198.</ref>\n \nAt the same time Brickhill had been approached by John Pudney who had recently joined London based publisher [[Evans Brothers]] as an editor with a proposal to write a book on the Stalag Luft 3 mass escape. This was eventually to be published as ''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]''.<ref name= Dando-CollinsP198/>\nWith the advance that Evans Brothers offered Brickhill he left his job and sailed to England in May 1949.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 199.</ref>\n\nOnce in England Brickhill asked the RAF about the status of the proposed history of 617 squadron, offering his services if they were still required. As the RAF had made no further progress in finding an alternative author, his offer was accepted.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 200.</ref>\nBrickhill approached Evans Brothers about an advance for the proposed book on 617 Squadron, but they were not interested in providing any advance until they saw a manuscript.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 206.</ref> \nAlready working on ''The Great Escape'', Brickhill also commenced simultaneous work on the 617 squadron history.\n\n''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]'' was published in 1950 and brought the incident to wide public attention. \n\nThe history of 617 Squadron and in particular its involvement in [[Operation Chastise|Operation ''Chastise'']] and the destruction of dams in the [[Ruhr (river)|Ruhr]] valley was published in 1951 as ''[[The Dam Busters (book)|The Dam Busters]]'', selling over one million copies in its first 50 years.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 233.</ref><ref name= RamsdenP20 >Ramsden. Page 20.</ref>\n\nFollowing the success of ''The Dam Busters'' [[Robert Clark (film executive)|Robert Clark]] the head of production at [[Associated British Picture Corporation]] approached Brickhill about acquiring the screen rights to the book. The company's production manager was of the opinion that there were too many people and raids involved, and that they would not be able to film the book in its entirety. As a result he requested that Brickhill provide a condensed film treatment. Brickhill agree to do it without payment in the hope of selling the screen rights. To assist , Clark teamed him up with Walter Mycroft who was the company's Director of Production.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 237.</ref>  Brickhill decided to concentrate the film treatment on [[Operation Chastise]], and ignore the later raids.\n\nAssociated agreed with Brickhill on the film rights in December 1952 for what is believed to have been \u20a45,000.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 241.</ref>\n\nThe subsequent film was released in 1954 as ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]]''.\n\n==''Reach for the Sky''==\nAfter reading ''The Dam Busters'', [[Battle of Britain]] ace [[Douglas Bader]] approached Brickhill in 1951 about collaborating on his biography.<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 233 to 236.</ref> Brickhill agreed to undertake the project.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 239.</ref>\n\nAfter approaching several publishers about the proposed biography Brickhill's agent found that William Collins and Sons were prepared to offer the best terms, leading Brickhill to sign with them. However Brickhill felt guilty about not signing with John Pudney and Evans Brothers, who had previously been so supportive of him.  He consequently offered to write an anthology of escape stories for them, which they eventually published as ''Escape \u2013 Or Die''.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 240.</ref>\n\nThe resulting biography of Bader was published in 1954 as ''Reach for the Sky''. In the first few months alone, 172,000 copies were sold.<ref>Mackenzie. Page 164.</ref> The initial print run of 300,000 quickly sold out, as the biography became the biggest-selling hardback in post-war Britain.\n\nThe book was subsequently adapted for the screen and released in 1956 as a [[Reach for the Sky (1956 film)|feature film]]. Starring [[Kenneth More]] as Bader, it topped the box office in Britain that year.<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 303 to304.</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nBrickhill spent the rest of his life working on several unfinished film screenplays, novels and biographies, but was never able to repeat his successes of 1949 to 1954.\n\nIn 1969 he returned to live permanently in Australia.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 355.</ref> Brickhill died in [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]] on 23 April 1991 aged 74.<ref name=ADB>{{cite book|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/brickhill-paul-chester-14647 |title=Brickhill, Paul Chester (1916\u20131991) |first=Craig|last=Wilcox|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|via=Australian Dictionary of Biography}}</ref> See also John Ramsland's update.<ref>John A Ramsland. ''The Bestselling Mosman Author: Paul Brickhill, RAAF & POW Hero'' in ''ISAA Review'' Vol 17 No.1 2019, Journal of the Independent Scholars Association of Australia Inc.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAfter first meeting her while travelling by ship from Australia to England in 1949, the 33-year-old Brickhill married 21-year-old Margot Slater, also an Australian, in [[St. Michael's Church, Chester Square]], Chester Square, [[Pimlico]] on 22 April 1950. They divorced on 20 July 1964 after a tempestuous marriage.<ref name=\"afr.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afr.com/lifestyle/paul-brickhill-australias-glamorous-heromaker-20160831-gr5byz|title=Paul Brickhill, Australia's glamorous hero-maker of \"The Great Escape\" and \"The Dam Busters\"|date=2 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=ADB/> Margot later married [[Devon Minchin]].<ref>https://www.asial.com.au/documents/item/41</ref>\n\nPaul and Margot Brickhill had two children: Timothy Paul (14 April 1954\u2013  )<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 283.</ref> and Tempe Melinda (August 1957\u2013  ).<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 307.</ref> After working as a fashion model Tempe became manager of [[Issey Miyake]] London, CEO of [[Issey Miyake]] Europe and a director of [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Fran\u00e7aise de la Couture]].<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 372.</ref>\n\n==Biographies about Brickhill==\n\nHis life was the subject of a 2016 biography, ''The Hero Maker: A Biography of Paul Brickhill'', by [[Stephen Dando-Collins]]<ref name=\"afr.com\"/> and ''Flying into Danger: The Paul Brickhill Story'' by John Ramsland.\n\n==Bibliography==\nBrickill wrote the following books:\n* ''Escape to Danger'' (with Conrad Norton). London: Faber and Faber, 1946.\n* ''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]''. New York: Norton, 1950.\n* ''[[The Dam Busters (book)|The Dam Busters]]''. London: Evans, 1951.\n* ''Escape \u2013 Or Die: Authentic Stories of the R.A.F. Escaping Society''. London: Evans, 1952.\n* ''Reach for the Sky: The Story of [[Douglas Bader]] DSO, DFC''. London: Collins, 1954. \n* ''The Deadline''. London: Collins, 1962. (US title ''War of Nerves'')<ref>{{Citation| title=War of nerves / Paul Brickhill |author1=Brickhill, Paul, 1916\u20131991 | year=1963 | publisher=Morrow | language=English}}</ref>\n* ''Three Great Air Stories''. London: Collins, 1970.\n\n==Film adaptations==\nThree books by Brickhill were made into feature films: ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]]'' (1955), ''[[Reach for the Sky - The story of Douglas Bader]]'' (1956), and ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' (1963).\n\n''Deadline'' became an episode of the ''[[Bob Hope Presents the Chrysler Theatre]]'' [[anthology series]] entitled ''War of Nerves'' that was first broadcast on 5 January 1964.<ref>{{cite web | title = War of Nerves | publisher = IMDb | date = | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0528248/ | accessdate = February 15, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* \"Brickhill, Paul Chester Jerome 1916\u20131991.\" ''Contemporary Authors, New Revision Series'', 69: 68\u201369.\n*{{cite book | last = Dando-Collins | first = Stephen | title = The Hero Maker: A Biography of Paul Brickhill | location= Sydney | publisher = Penguin Random House Australia | date = 2016 | type = Paperback | isbn = 978-0-85798-812-6}}\n*{{cite book | last = Mackenzie | first = S. P.   | title = Bader's War | location= London | publisher = Spellmount Publishers | date = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-7524-5534-1}}\n*{{cite book | last = Ramsden | first = John | title = The Dam Busters: A British Film Guide | location= London | publisher = I.N. Tauris & Co | date = 2003 | type = Paperback | isbn = 1-86064-636-0}}\n*{{cite book | last = Ramsland | first = John | title = Flying Into Danger: The Paul Brickhill Story | location= Carlton, Australia | publisher = Brolga Publishing | date = 2016 | type = Paperback | isbn = 978-1-92536-768-3}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0108595|Paul Brickhill}}\n*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CEEDE1531F935A15757C0A967958260 NY Times obituary]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brickhill, Paul}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Writers from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Australian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war held by Germany]]\n[[Category:Royal Australian Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Great Escape from Stalag Luft III]]\n[[Category:Australian World War II pilots]]\n[[Category:Australian prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:People educated at North Sydney Boys High School]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Paul Brickhill\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = Paul Chester Jerome Brickhill\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1916|12|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], Australia\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1991|04|23|1916|12|20|df=y}} \n| death_place      = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = \n| language         = \n| residence        = \n| nationality      = \n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| home_town        = \n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = ''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]''<br /> ''[[The Dam Busters (book)|The Dam Busters]]''<br /> ''[[Reach for The Sky (book)|Reach for The Sky]]''\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc.; or omit -->\n}}\n'''Paul Chester Jerome Brickhill''' (20 December 1916{{spaced ndash}}23 April 1991) was an Australian fighter pilot, prisoner of war, and author who wrote ''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]'', ''[[The Dam Busters (book)|The Dam Busters]]'', and ''Reach for the Sky''.\n\n==Early life==\nBrickhill was born in [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] to [[journalist]] George Russell Brickhill (1879\u20131964) and Izitella Victoria Brickhill (nee Bradshaw).<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 17 & 19.</ref> He was the third son of the couple's five children, the others being Russell (1911\u20132002), Ayde Geoffrey (1914\u2013 ), Lloyd (1918\u20132011), and Clive (1923\u20132009).<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 21, 24 & 26.</ref> When Brickhill was 11 the family moved to Sydney where he was educated at [[North Sydney Boys High School]]. A classmate, and friend, was actor [[Peter Finch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/newslocal/north-shore/his-great-escape-how-famous-author-paul-brickhill-ended-his-days-in-a-small-sydney-flat/news-story/8c2af4c28654cf56bc535d18b68ea3d0|title=Great Escape author\u2019s mystery life|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nBrickhill left school in 1931 as his father had been made redundant by the Depression. While his other brothers continued with their education it was necessary for Brickhill, who was regarded as the least academic of the children, to get a job to assist his older brother Russell in bringing money into the family.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 37.</ref> He was sacked from his first two jobs due to his stutter. He then got a job as office boy and then lift boy at the Adelaide Steamship Company. That job did not last long, as Peter Finch, who was by now working as a copy boy, was able to convince a news editor at ''[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]]''  to interview Brickhill in 1932.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 39.</ref> Brickhill was hired as a copy boy, and within a year promoted to cadet journalist. Within a few years he had worked his way up to journalist, and by 1940 was a sub-editor.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 47.</ref>\n\n==World War II==\nBrickhill was initially unimpressed by war fever, until the shock of the invasion of France and subsequent withdrawal from Dunkirk, coupled with boredom with his deskbound sub-editor job, caused him to enlist on 6 January 1941 with the [[Royal Australian Air Force]] (RAAF).<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 49.</ref>\nHis flight training commenced in March 1941 at the Number 8 Elementary Flying Training School at Narrandera, New South Wales as undertaken in Australia \nUnder the [[British Commonwealth Air Training Plan|Empire Air Training Scheme]]. Brickhill undertook advanced training as a [[Fighter aircraft|fighter]] pilot in Canada and the United Kingdom before being assigned to [[No. 92 Squadron RAF]], a unit equipped with [[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]]s and part of the [[Desert Air Force]] in North Africa. \n\nOn 17 March 1943, he was shot down over [[Tunisia]] and became a [[prisoner of war]].<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 1 to 12.</ref> He was flown to Italy on 23 March, then sent by train to Germany. After initially being held at the [[Dulag Luft]] at [[Oberursel (Taunus) | Oberursel]], a central receiving and interrogation station for captured enemy airman for the [[Luftwaffe]], he was sent to [[Stalag Luft III]], in [[Lower Silesia]], 150 km southeast of Berlin, arriving there on 4 April 1943.<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 84 to 85.</ref>\nBrickhill became involved with organizing the camp's escape, initially as a lookout or \"stoogie\", before volunteering to work as a digger on the \"Tom\" tunnel\".<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 102 to 105.</ref> He developed [[claustrophobia]], and as a result was eventually reassigned and put in charge of security for the forgers. Because of his claustrophobia and the risk that he would panic and block the escape of others behind him, he was not allowed to take part in the [[Stalag Luft III escape|mass escape attempt]], which is today known as \"The Great Escape\".<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 124.</ref>\n\nFollowing the announcement of the murder of the escapees who had been recaptured following the Great Escape, Brickhill became determined to document the event. Discussing the subject with fellow prisoner Conrad Norton, they identified that many of their fellow prisoners had other tales of daring escapes, and that they could provide the possibility of publishing a book following the end of the war. As Brickhill had been involved in \"The Great Escape\", he concentrated on that story, while Norton collected individual tales.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 138.</ref> As prisoners were forbidden from writing anything other than letters and postcards, they collected every piece of paper they could find and, writing in as small a hand as possible, they collected stories and hid them from the guards. \n\nOn [[D-Day]], while still in captivity, Brickhill heard on German radio of two huge Allied armadas heading towards [[Cap d'Antifer]] and [[Calais]].  These were diversions created by [[No. 617 Squadron RAF]] to fool the Germans, however, a fact he learned months later.\n\n==Returns to journalism==\n\nFollowing the end of the war, while the terms of his enlistment with the RAAF had been that he had to serve for 12 months following the cessation of hostilities, Brickhill was granted six months' leave without pay. During his leave he returned to journalism, working as a London-based correspondent for [[Associated Newspapers]]. Meanwhile outside of working hours he had typed up his and Norton's stories and selected David Higham as their literary agent.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 162.</ref> With Higham's help the manuscript was accepted by [[Faber & Faber]] and published as ''Escape to Danger'' in 1946.\n\nAfter working for Associated Newspapers for a period, Brickhill returned to Australia, taking a job as a sub-editor at ''[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]]'' newspaper in Sydney, Australia.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 194.</ref>\n\nBrickhill and Norton had agreed that each would retain the copyright to the chapters that they had written for ''Escape to Danger''. As a result while awaiting for sufficient stocks of paper to be obtained to print the book, Brickhill was able to sell a condensed version of his chapter on the Great Escape to several newspapers in Australia.\n\n==The Great Escape and The Dam Busters==\nAfter the end of World War II, John Nerney, head of the [[Air Historical Branch]] of the [[British Air Ministry]] identified the need for a history of 617 Squadron. While trying to find a suitable author he discussed the issue with [[John Pudney]], who was an editor at ''[[News Review]]''. Pudney had liked ''Escape to Danger'' and suggested that Brickhill be considered.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 196.</ref>\n\nFollowing up Pudney's recommendation, Nerney approached Brickhill in February 1949, who jumped at the offer. While doing all it could to assist his research the Air Ministry could only provide Brickhill with a small honorarium, and no guarantee of publication other than as a government produced publication.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 197.</ref> In an attempt to obtain an advance which would pay enough for him to leave his current job as a sub-editor at ''[[The Sun (Sydney)|The Sun]]'' and relocate to England Brickhill approached a number of Australian publishers to see if they were interested in an Australian edition of the book. None was interested so Brickhill was forced to decline Nerney's offer.<ref name=Dando-CollinsP198>Dando-Collins. Page 198.</ref>\n \nAt the same time Brickhill had been approached by John Pudney who had recently joined London based publisher [[Evans Brothers]] as an editor with a proposal to write a book on the Stalag Luft 3 mass escape. This was eventually to be published as ''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]''.<ref name= Dando-CollinsP198/>\nWith the advance that Evans Brothers offered Brickhill he left his job and sailed to England in May 1949.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 199.</ref>\n\nOnce in England Brickhill asked the RAF about the status of the proposed history of 617 squadron, offering his services if they were still required. As the RAF had made no further progress in finding an alternative author, his offer was accepted.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 200.</ref>\nBrickhill approached Evans Brothers about an advance for the proposed book on 617 Squadron, but they were not interested in providing any advance until they saw a manuscript.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 206.</ref> \nAlready working on ''The Great Escape'', Brickhill also commenced simultaneous work on the 617 squadron history.\n\n''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]'' was published in 1950 and brought the incident to wide public attention. \n\nThe history of 617 Squadron and in particular its involvement in [[Operation Chastise|Operation ''Chastise'']] and the destruction of dams in the [[Ruhr (river)|Ruhr]] valley was published in 1951 as ''[[The Dam Busters (book)|The Dam Busters]]'', selling over one million copies in its first 50 years.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 233.</ref><ref name= RamsdenP20 >Ramsden. Page 20.</ref>\n\nFollowing the success of ''The Dam Busters'' [[Robert Clark (film executive)|Robert Clark]] the head of production at [[Associated British Picture Corporation]] approached Brickhill about acquiring the screen rights to the book. The company's production manager was of the opinion that there were too many people and raids involved, and that they would not be able to film the book in its entirety. As a result he requested that Brickhill provide a condensed film treatment. Brickhill agree to do it without payment in the hope of selling the screen rights. To assist , Clark teamed him up with Walter Mycroft who was the company's Director of Production.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 237.</ref>  Brickhill decided to concentrate the film treatment on [[Operation Chastise]], and ignore the later raids.\n\nAssociated agreed with Brickhill on the film rights in December 1952 for what is believed to have been \u20a45,000.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 241.</ref>\n\nThe subsequent film was released in 1954 as ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]]''.\n\n==''Reach for the Sky''==\nAfter reading ''The Dam Busters'', [[Battle of Britain]] ace [[Douglas Bader]] approached Brickhill in 1951 about collaborating on his biography.<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 233 to 236.</ref> Brickhill agreed to undertake the project.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 239.</ref>\n\nAfter approaching several publishers about the proposed biography Brickhill's agent found that William Collins and Sons were prepared to offer the best terms, leading Brickhill to sign with them. However Brickhill felt guilty about not signing with John Pudney and Evans Brothers, who had previously been so supportive of him.  He consequently offered to write an anthology of escape stories for them, which they eventually published as ''Escape \u2013 Or Die''.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 240.</ref>\n\nThe resulting biography of Bader was published in 1954 as ''Reach for the Sky''. In the first few months alone, 172,000 copies were sold.<ref>Mackenzie. Page 164.</ref> The initial print run of 300,000 quickly sold out, as the biography became the biggest-selling hardback in post-war Britain.\n\nThe book was subsequently adapted for the screen and released in 1956 as a [[Reach for the Sky (1956 film)|feature film]]. Starring [[Kenneth More]] as Bader, it topped the box office in Britain that year.<ref>Dando-Collins. Pages 303 to304.</ref>\n\n==Later life==\nBrickhill spent the rest of his life working on several unfinished film screenplays, novels and biographies, but was never able to repeat his successes of 1949 to 1954.\n\nIn 1969 he returned to live permanently in Australia.<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 355.</ref> Brickhill died in [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]] on 23 April 1991 aged 74.<ref name=ADB>{{cite book|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/brickhill-paul-chester-14647 |title=Brickhill, Paul Chester (1916\u20131991) |first=Craig|last=Wilcox|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|via=Australian Dictionary of Biography}}</ref> See also John Ramsland's update.<ref>John A Ramsland. ''The Bestselling Mosman Author: Paul Brickhill, RAAF & POW Hero'' in ''ISAA Review'' Vol 17 No.1 2019, Journal of the Independent Scholars Association of Australia Inc.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAfter first meeting her while travelling by ship from Australia to England in 1949, the 33-year-old Brickhill married 21-year-old Margot Slater, also an Australian, in [[St. Michael's Church, Chester Square]], Chester Square, [[Pimlico]] on 22 April 1950. They divorced on 20 July 1964 after a tempestuous marriage.<ref name=\"afr.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.afr.com/lifestyle/paul-brickhill-australias-glamorous-heromaker-20160831-gr5byz|title=Paul Brickhill, Australia's glamorous hero-maker of \"The Great Escape\" and \"The Dam Busters\"|date=2 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=ADB/> Margot later married [[Devon Minchin]].<ref>https://www.asial.com.au/documents/item/41</ref>\n\nPaul and Margot Brickhill had two children: Timothy Paul (14 April 1954\u2013  )<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 283.</ref> and Tempe Melinda (August 1957\u2013  ).<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 307.</ref> After working as a fashion model Tempe became manager of [[Issey Miyake]] London, CEO of [[Issey Miyake]] Europe and a director of [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Fran\u00e7aise de la Couture]].<ref>Dando-Collins. Page 372.</ref>\n\n==Biographies about Brickhill==\n\nHis life was the subject of a 2016 biography, ''The Hero Maker: A Biography of Paul Brickhill'', by [[Stephen Dando-Collins]]<ref name=\"afr.com\"/> and ''Flying into Danger: The Paul Brickhill Story'' by John Ramsland.\n\n==Bibliography==\nBrickill wrote the following books:\n* ''Escape to Danger'' (with Conrad Norton). London: Faber and Faber, 1946.\n* ''[[The Great Escape (book)|The Great Escape]]''. New York: Norton, 1950.\n* ''[[The Dam Busters (book)|The Dam Busters]]''. London: Evans, 1951.\n* ''Escape \u2013 Or Die: Authentic Stories of the R.A.F. Escaping Society''. London: Evans, 1952.\n* ''Reach for the Sky: The Story of [[Douglas Bader]] DSO, DFC''. London: Collins, 1954. \n* ''The Deadline''. London: Collins, 1962. (US title ''War of Nerves'')<ref>{{Citation| title=War of nerves / Paul Brickhill |author1=Brickhill, Paul, 1916\u20131991 | year=1963 | publisher=Morrow | language=English}}</ref>\n* ''Three Great Air Stories''. London: Collins, 1970.\n\n==Film adaptations==\nThree books by Brickhill were made into feature films: ''[[The Dam Busters (film)|The Dam Busters]]'' (1955), ''[[Reach for the Sky - The story of Douglas Bader]]'' (1956), and ''[[The Great Escape (film)|The Great Escape]]'' (1963).\n\n''Deadline'' became an episode of the ''[[Bob Hope Presents the Chrysler Theatre]]'' [[anthology series]] entitled ''War of Nerves'' that was first broadcast on 5 January 1964.<ref>{{cite web | title = War of Nerves | publisher = IMDb | date = | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0528248/ | accessdate = February 15, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* \"Brickhill, Paul Chester Jerome 1916\u20131991.\" ''Contemporary Authors, New Revision Series'', 69: 68\u201369.\n*{{cite book | last = Dando-Collins | first = Stephen | title = The Hero Maker: A Biography of Paul Brickhill | location= Sydney | publisher = Penguin Random House Australia | date = 2016 | type = Paperback | isbn = 978-0-85798-812-6}}\n*{{cite book | last = Mackenzie | first = S. P.   | title = Bader's War | location= London | publisher = Spellmount Publishers | date = 2008 | isbn = 978-0-7524-5534-1}}\n*{{cite book | last = Ramsden | first = John | title = The Dam Busters: A British Film Guide | location= London | publisher = I.N. Tauris & Co | date = 2003 | type = Paperback | isbn = 1-86064-636-0}}\n*{{cite book | last = Ramsland | first = John | title = Flying Into Danger: The Paul Brickhill Story | location= Carlton, Australia | publisher = Brolga Publishing | date = 2016 | type = Paperback | isbn = 978-1-92536-768-3}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0108595|Paul Brickhill}}\n*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0CEEDE1531F935A15757C0A967958260 NY Times obituary]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brickhill, Paul}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1991 deaths]]\n[[Category:Writers from Melbourne]]\n[[Category:Australian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war held by Germany]]\n[[Category:Royal Australian Air Force officers]]\n[[Category:Participants in the Great Escape from Stalag Luft III]]\n[[Category:Australian World War II pilots]]\n[[Category:Australian prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:People educated at North Sydney Boys High School]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian writers]]\n", "name_user": "Sfjohna", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReturns to journalism", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Brickhill"}
{"title_page": "Petar Remete", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Petar Remete\n|image               = \n|caption             = \n|fullname            = \n|birth_date          = {{Birth date|1937|8|13|df=y}}\n|birth_place         = [[Ilok]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]]\n|death_date          = {{Death date and age|2011|10|22|1937|8|13|df=y}}\n|death_place         = \n|height              = \n|position            = Forward, left and right winger\n|youthyears1         = \n|youthclubs1         = \n|years1              = 1954\u20131955\n|clubs1              = Sloga Vukovar\n|caps1               = \n|goals1              = \n|years2              = 1955\u20131961\n|clubs2              = [[FK Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka|Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka]]\n|caps2               = \n|goals2              = \n|years3              = 1961\u20131962\n|clubs3              = [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|caps3               = 17\n|goals3              = 4\n|years4              = 1962\u20131963\n|clubs4              = [[NK Tre\u0161njevka|Tre\u0161njevka]]\n|caps4               = \n|goals4              = \n|years5              = 1963\u20131964\n|clubs5              = [[NK Karlovac|Karlovac]]\n|caps5               = \n|goals5              = \n|years6              = 1964\u20131965\n|clubs6              = [[NK Celje|Kladivar]]\n|caps6               = \n|goals6              = \n|years7              = 1965\u20131966\n|clubs7              = [[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva Zagreb]]\n|caps7               = \n|goals7              = \n|years8              = 1966\u20131973\n|clubs8              = [[FK Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka|Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka]]\n|caps8               = \n|goals8              = \n|nationalyears1      =\n|nationalteam1       = [[Yugoslavia national under-21 football team|Yugoslavia U-21]]\n|nationalcaps1       = 3\n|nationalgoals1      = ?\n}}\n\n'''Petar Remete''' (13 August 1937 \u2013 22 October 2011) was a [[Croats|Croatian]] [[Association football|football]]er.\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Ilok]], [[Danube Banovina]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]], he begin his career in 1954 playing with Sloga Vukovar, a traditional club from that town neighbouring to his birthplace, and predecessor of nowadays [[HNK Vukovar '91]]. After only one season, he moved to [[FK Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka|Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka]] where he stayed 6 seasons. His great performances as forward earned him 3 appearances in the [[Yugoslavia national under-21 football team|Yugoslav U-21]] team, and, after crowning himself top-scorer of the [[Yugoslav Second League]] in 1960, he called the attention of the big clubs, ending up by signing with [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] in 1961. During his time at Dinamo, he played mostly as either left or right winger, and he scored a total of 27 goals in 46 appearances, of which 17 appearances and 4 goals were in the [[Yugoslav First League]].<ref name=\"povijest\">[https://povijest.gnkdinamo.hr/popis-igra%C4%8Da/petar-remete.html Petar Remete - Biografija] at Povijest Dinama {{in lang|hr}}</ref> He then went on and played with [[NK Tre\u0161njevka|Tre\u0161njevka]], [[NK Karlovac|Karlovac]], [[NK Celje|Kladivar]] and [[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva]], one season with each of the clubs, before returning to [[FK Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka|Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka]] in 1966<ref>Petar Remete at Istorija ex Yu fudbala {{in lang|sr}}</ref> and played there until he finished his career in 1973.<ref>[http://footballfacts.ru/players/2149368-remete-petar Petar Remete] at footballfacts.ru</ref> He died on October 22, 2011.<ref name=\"povijest\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Yugoslav Second League]] top-scorer: 1960<ref name=\"povijest\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Remete, Petar}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ilok]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Croatian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:OFK Ba\u010dka players]]\n[[Category:GNK Dinamo Zagreb players]]\n[[Category:NK Tre\u0161njevka players]]\n[[Category:NK Karlovac players]]\n[[Category:NK Celje players]]\n[[Category:NK Lokomotiva players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n\n{{Croatia-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name                = Petar Remete\n|image               = \n|caption             = \n|fullname            = \n|birth_date          = {{Birth date|1937|8|13|df=y}}\n|birth_place         = [[Ilok]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]]\n|death_date          = {{Death date and age|2011|10|22|1937|8|13|df=y}}\n|death_place         = \n|height              = \n|position            = Forward, left and right winger\n|youthyears1         = \n|youthclubs1         = \n|years1              = 1954\u20131955\n|clubs1              = Sloga Vukovar\n|caps1               = \n|goals1              = \n|years2              = 1955\u20131961\n|clubs2              = [[FK Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka|Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka]]\n|caps2               = \n|goals2              = \n|years3              = 1961\u20131962\n|clubs3              = [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]]\n|caps3               = 17\n|goals3              = 4\n|years4              = 1962\u20131963\n|clubs4              = [[NK Tre\u0161njevka|Tre\u0161njevka]]\n|caps4               = \n|goals4              = \n|years5              = 1963\u20131964\n|clubs5              = [[NK Karlovac|Karlovac]]\n|caps5               = \n|goals5              = \n|years6              = 1964\u20131965\n|clubs6              = [[NK Celje|Kladivar]]\n|caps6               = \n|goals6              = \n|years7              = 1965\u20131966\n|clubs7              = [[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva Zagreb]]\n|caps7               = \n|goals7              = \n|years8              = 1966\u20131973\n|clubs8              = [[FK Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka|Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka]]\n|caps8               = \n|goals8              = \n|nationalyears1      =\n|nationalteam1       = [[Yugoslavia national under-21 football team|Yugoslavia U-21]]\n|nationalcaps1       = 3\n|nationalgoals1      = ?\n}}\n\n'''Petar Remete''' (13 August 1937 \u2013 22 October 2011) is a former [[Croats|Croatian]] [[Association football|football]]er.\n\n==Career==\nBorn in [[Ilok]], [[Danube Banovina]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]], he begin his career in 1954 playing with Sloga Vukovar, a traditional club from that town neighbouring to his birthplace, and predecessor of nowadays [[HNK Vukovar '91]]. After only one season, he moved to [[FK Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka|Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka]] where he stayed 6 seasons. His great performances as forward earned him 3 appearances in the [[Yugoslavia national under-21 football team|Yugoslav U-21]] team, and, after crowning himself top-scorer of the [[Yugoslav Second League]] in 1960, he called the attention of the big clubs, ending up by signing with [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] in 1961. During his time at Dinamo, he played mostly as either left or right winger, and he scored a total of 27 goals in 46 appearances, of which 17 appearances and 4 goals were in the [[Yugoslav First League]].<ref name=\"povijest\">[https://povijest.gnkdinamo.hr/popis-igra%C4%8Da/petar-remete.html Petar Remete - Biografija] at Povijest Dinama {{in lang|hr}}</ref> He then went on and played with [[NK Tre\u0161njevka|Tre\u0161njevka]], [[NK Karlovac|Karlovac]], [[NK Celje|Kladivar]] and [[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva]], one season with each of the clubs, before returning to [[FK Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka|Ba\u010dka Ba\u010dka Palanka]] in 1966<ref>Petar Remete at Istorija ex Yu fudbala {{in lang|sr}}</ref> and played there until he finished his career in 1973.<ref>[http://footballfacts.ru/players/2149368-remete-petar Petar Remete] at footballfacts.ru</ref> He died on October 22, 2011.<ref name=\"povijest\"/>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[Yugoslav Second League]] top-scorer: 1960<ref name=\"povijest\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Remete, Petar}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ilok]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav footballers]]\n[[Category:Croatian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:OFK Ba\u010dka players]]\n[[Category:GNK Dinamo Zagreb players]]\n[[Category:NK Tre\u0161njevka players]]\n[[Category:NK Karlovac players]]\n[[Category:NK Celje players]]\n[[Category:NK Lokomotiva players]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav First League players]]\n\n{{Croatia-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "FkpCascais", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petar_Remete"}
{"title_page": "Pelew flying fox", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Pteropus pelewensis yapensis.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Pteropus pelewensis yapensis''\n| status = NT\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name = IUCN>{{Cite journal | author = Wiles, G. | title = ''Pteropus pelewensis'' | journal = [[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume = 2008 | page = e.T136387A4284457 | publisher = [[IUCN]] | date = 2008 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2008.RLTS.T136387A4284457.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Pteropus\n| species = pelewensis\n| authority = [[Knud Andersen (mammalogist)|K. Andersen]], 1908\n| synonyms = * ''Pteropus mariannus pelewensis''\n| range_map = Pelew Flying Fox area.png\n| range_map_caption = Pelew flying fox range\n}}\n\nThe '''Pelew flying fox''' (''Pteropus pelewensis'') is a species of [[megabat]] in the genus ''[[Pteropus]]'' found in the [[Pelew Islands]]. A subspecies found on [[Yap]], the '''Yap flying fox''', is considered as a separate species by some authorities.<ref>D.E. Wilson & D.M. Reeder, 2005: ''Mammal Species of the World: A Taxonomic and Geographic Reference. Third Edition''. The Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore</ref>  The species is listed as \"Near Threatened\" by the IUCN due to commercial and small-scale hunting; commercial hunting for the species was banned in 1994, but local exploitation is commonplace.  The species is listed on [[CITES]] appendix I.<ref name=IUCN />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Pteropodidae|P.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q510172}}\n\n[[Category:Pteropus]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1908]]\n[[Category:Bats of Oceania]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Knud Andersen]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Palau]]\n\n{{fruit-bat-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Pteropus pelewensis yapensis.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Pteropus pelewensis yapensis''\n| status = NT\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name = IUCN>{{Cite journal | author = Wiles, G. | title = ''Pteropus pelewensis'' | journal = [[The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species]] | volume = 2008 | page = e.T136387A4284457 | publisher = [[IUCN]] | date = 2008 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2008.RLTS.T136387A4284457.en }}</ref>\n| genus = Pteropus\n| species = pelewensis\n| authority = [[Knud Andersen (mammalogist)|K. Andersen]], 1908\n| synonyms = * ''Pteropus mariannus pelewensis''\n| range_map = Pelew Flying Fox area.png\n| range_map_caption = Pelew flying fox range\n}}\n\nThe '''Pelew flying fox''' (''Pteropus pelewensis'') is a species of [[megabat]] in the genus ''[[Pteropus]]'' found in the [[Pelew Islands]]. A subspecies found on [[Yap]], the '''Yap flying fox''', is considered as a separate species by some authorities. <ref>D.E. Wilson & D.M. Reeder, 2005: ''Mammal Species of the World: A Taxonomic and Geographic Reference. Third Edition''. The Johns Hopkins University Press, Baltimore</ref>  The species is listed as \"Near Threatened\" by the IUCN due to commercial and small-scale hunting; commercial hunting for the species was banned in 1994, but local exploitation is commonplace.  The species is listed on [[CITES]] appendix I.<ref name=IUCN />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Pteropodidae|P.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q510172}}\n\n[[Category:Pteropus]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1908]]\n[[Category:Bats of Oceania]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Knud Andersen]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Palau]]\n\n{{fruit-bat-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Loopy30", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pelew_flying_fox"}
{"title_page": "Orion (roller coaster)", "text_new": "{{Infobox roller coaster\n| logo                 = Ki-Orion-Logo.png\n| logodimensions       = \n| image                = Ki-Orion-layout.jpg\n| imagedimensions      = \n| caption              = \n| previousnames        = \n| location             = Kings Island\n| locationarticle      = <!--Must not be linked.-->\n| section              = Coney Mall\n| subsection           = <!--This is X-Base until Area 72 exists-->[[Kings Island#X-Base|X-Base]]\n| coordinates          = {{Coord|39|20|33.84|N|84|15|45.82|W|display=title,inline|region:US-OH_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n| status               = Under Construction\n| opened               = {{Start date|2020}}\n| soft_opened          = <!--Open {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| year                 = 2020\n| closed               = <!--Open {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| cost                 = $30 Million\n| previousattraction   = [[Firehawk (roller coaster)|Firehawk]]\n| replacement          =\n| type                 = Steel<!--Must be \"Steel\" or \"Wood\", nothing else. Must not be linked.-->\n| type2                = <!--Must not be linked, will auto-categorize the coaster.-->\n| manufacturer         = Bolliger & Mabillard\n| designer             = \n| model                = Hyper Coaster<!-- This is the name of B&M's model. \"Giga\" is an industry name and doesn't belong here. -->\n| track                =\n| lift                 = Cable [[lift hill]]\n| height_ft            = 287\n| drop_ft              = 300\n| length_ft            = 5,321\n| speed_mph            = 91\n| inversions           = 0\n| duration             = 3:00\n| angle                = 85<ref>{{cite web | title=Kings Island\u2019s new giga coaster uses rolling terrain to its advantage | website=daytondailynews | date=October 8, 2019 | url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/kings-island-new-giga-coaster-uses-rolling-terrain-its-advantage/gsPH2j2l1E1thR5MNVA5yO/ | access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n| capacity             = 1,650\n| acceleration         = <!--Expression in full form e.g. \"X to Y mph (\u03c7 to \u03c8 km/h) in Z seconds\". -->\n| acceleration_from    = <!--Initial speed in mph or km/h defaults to zero, only numeric characters-->\n| acceleration_mph     = <!--Final speed in mph may contain only numeric characters-->\n| acceleration_in      = <!--Number of seconds may contain words -->\n| gforce               =\n| restriction_in       = 54\n| trains               = 3\n| carspertrain         = 8\n| rowspercar           = 1\n| ridersperrow         = 4\n| virtual_queue_name   =\n| virtual_queue_image  = <!--Use ONLY the filename, not a full [[File:]] link-->\n| virtual_queue_status = <!--should be available if above fields are used-->\n| single_rider         = <!--Must be \"available\" if available.-->\n| accessible           = <!--Must be \"available\" if available.-->\n| transfer_accessible  = <!--Must be \"available\" if available.-->\n| custom_label_1       =\n| custom_value_1       =\n| custom_label_2       =\n| custom_value_2       =\n| rcdb_number          = 11437\n| video                = <!--Use ONLY the filename, not a full [[File:]] link-->\n| videosize            = <!--Must be expressed in pixels (px); default is 250px-->\n| videocaption         = \n}}\n\n'''Orion''' is an upcoming [[steel roller coaster]] located at [[Kings Island]] amusement park in [[Mason, Ohio]]. It is a Hyper Coaster model from manufacturer [[Bolliger & Mabillard]], which will become the seventh [[giga coaster]] in the world and the largest investment in park history, costing an estimated $30 million.<ref name=\"Reveal-PlainDealer\" /><ref name=\"Reveal-CincyEnquirer\" /> Orion will stand {{Convert|287|ft}}, feature a {{Convert|300|ft|m|adj=mid|drop}}, and reach a maximum speed of {{Convert|91|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Reveal-PlainDealer\" /><ref name=\"Reveal-CincyEnquirer\"/> Its track will stretch {{Convert|5,321|ft}} on a site formerly occupied by [[Firehawk (roller coaster)|Firehawk]], located in the [[Kings Island#X-Base|Area 72]] section of the park.<ref name=\"Reveal-KI\" />\n\n==History==\nIn early 2019, Kings Island submitted construction blueprints to the City of Mason for approval.<ref name=\"Orion Blueprints\" /> Dennis Speigel, co-founder and previous employee of Kings Island, stated that plans indicated a new roller coaster was being built, with a likely height estimate of at least {{convert|300|ft}} that would qualify it as a [[giga coaster]].<ref name=\"Orion Blueprints\" /> The plans were approved on April 24, 2019.<ref name=\"Orion Blueprints\" /> Cedar Fair also applied for national trademarks for the names ''Orion'' and ''Polaris'' as a marketing [[Teaser campaign|teaser tactic]] to keep enthusiasts guessing between the two.<ref name=\"Orion Blueprints\">{{cite web |last1=Matarese |first1=John |title=Kings Island files blueprints for new coaster |url=https://www.wcpo.com/money/consumer/dont-waste-your-money/kings-island-files-blueprints-for-new-coaster |website=wcpo.com |publisher=WCPO Cincinnati |accessdate=August 16, 2019 |date=May 9, 2019}}</ref> On August 15, 2019, Kings Island held an evening event open to both the media and public that officially announced the new coaster as Orion.<ref name=\"Reveal-KI\" /> It was confirmed to have a {{Convert|300|ft|m|adj=mid|drop}}, making it the seventh giga coaster in the world.<ref name=\"Reveal-PlainDealer\">{{cite news |last1=Glaser |first1=Susan |title=Kings Island announces new space-themed coaster Orion, with 300-foot first hill |url=https://www.cleveland.com/entertainment/2019/08/kings-island-announces-new-space-themed-coaster-orion-with-300-foot-first-hill.html |accessdate=August 16, 2019 |work=The Plain Dealer |date=August 15, 2019 |quote=Koontz said the coaster represented \u201cthe single largest investment in Kings Island history.\u201d}}</ref><ref name=\"Reveal-CincyEnquirer\">{{cite news |last1=Mitchell |first1=Madeline |title=Kings Island announces newest roller coaster, Orion, park's largest and longest coaster |url=https://www.cincinnati.com/story/entertainment/2019/08/15/kings-island-big-announcement/2018843001/ |accessdate=August 16, 2019 |work=Cincinnati Enquirer |date=August 15, 2019}}</ref> The announcement also stated that the unofficial X-Base section of the park will be renamed Area 72 in 2020.<ref name=\"Reveal-KI\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.visitkingsisland.com/explore/orion|title=Orion: Kings Island|publisher=Kings Island|accessdate=August 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Orion's train design was revealed at the annual IAAPA Amusement Expo in [[Orlando]].<ref name=\"Train reveal - ACE\" /><ref name=\"Train reveal - OCRegister\" /> Unlike previous train configurations from B&M that feature staggered, two-seat rows, Orion's trains were designed to seat four across in a straight line.<ref name=\"Train reveal - ACE\">{{cite web |last1=Ozana |first1=Rus |title=Kings Island Orion Train Cars Revealed |url=https://www.aceonline.org/news/478948/Kings-Island-Orion-Train-Cars-Revealed.htm |website=ACE Online |publisher=American Coaster Enthusiasts |accessdate=January 26, 2020 |date=November 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Train reveal - OCRegister\">{{cite news |last1=MacDonald |first1=Brady |title=11 best roller coaster and thrill ride reveals at massive Florida theme park expo |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2019/11/19/11-best-roller-coaster-and-thrill-ride-reveals-at-massive-florida-theme-park-expo/ |accessdate=January 26, 2020 |work=The Orange County Register |date=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Orion successfully completed its first test run.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=KingsIslandPR|number=1231391032320888832|title=After months of construction, Orion completed its first test run at 5:29 p.m. today. Video just released from park officials shows one of the ride\u2019s three trains climbing the lift hill and plummeting down the 300-foot first drop.|date=22 February 2020|website=www.twitter.com |author=King's Island PR |access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> It was originally scheduled to open on April 11, 2020, but the opening was postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"Postponed opening\">{{cite news |last1=Schwartzberg |first1=Eric |title=Kings Island postpones opening day for more than a month |url=https://www.journal-news.com/news/kings-island-postpones-opening-day-for-more-than-month/JHokCcTB8W3FTucKS3mjBL/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |work=Journal-News |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|url=https://www.visitkingsisland.com/explore/orion}}\n\n{{Kings Island}}\n[[Category:Roller coasters operated by Cedar Fair]]\n[[Category:Kings Island]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox roller coaster\n| logo                 = Ki-Orion-Logo.png\n| logodimensions       = \n| image                = Ki-Orion-layout.jpg\n| imagedimensions      = \n| caption              = \n| previousnames        = \n| location             = Kings Island\n| locationarticle      = <!--Must not be linked.-->\n| section              = Coney Mall\n| subsection           = <!--This is X-Base until Area 72 exists-->[[Kings Island#X-Base|X-Base]]\n| coordinates          = {{Coord|39|20|33.84|N|84|15|45.82|W|display=title,inline|region:US-OH_type:landmark_source:dewiki}}\n| status               = Under Construction\n| opened               = {{Start date|2020}}\n| soft_opened          = <!--Open {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| year                 = 2020\n| closed               = <!--Open {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| cost                 = $30 Million\n| previousattraction   = [[Firehawk (roller coaster)|Firehawk]]\n| replacement          =\n| type                 = Steel<!--Must be \"Steel\" or \"Wood\", nothing else. Must not be linked.-->\n| type2                = <!--Must not be linked, will auto-categorize the coaster.-->\n| manufacturer         = Bolliger & Mabillard\n| designer             = \n| model                = Hyper Coaster<!-- This is the name of B&M's model. \"Giga\" is an industry name and doesn't belong here. -->\n| track                =\n| lift                 = Chain [[lift hill]]\n| height_ft            = 287\n| drop_ft              = 300\n| length_ft            = 5,321\n| speed_mph            = 91\n| inversions           = 0\n| duration             = 3:00\n| angle                = 85<ref>{{cite web | title=Kings Island\u2019s new giga coaster uses rolling terrain to its advantage | website=daytondailynews | date=October 8, 2019 | url=https://www.daytondailynews.com/news/kings-island-new-giga-coaster-uses-rolling-terrain-its-advantage/gsPH2j2l1E1thR5MNVA5yO/ | access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n| capacity             = 1,650\n| acceleration         = <!--Expression in full form e.g. \"X to Y mph (\u03c7 to \u03c8 km/h) in Z seconds\". -->\n| acceleration_from    = <!--Initial speed in mph or km/h defaults to zero, only numeric characters-->\n| acceleration_mph     = <!--Final speed in mph may contain only numeric characters-->\n| acceleration_in      = <!--Number of seconds may contain words -->\n| gforce               =\n| restriction_in       = 54\n| trains               = 3\n| carspertrain         = 8\n| rowspercar           = 1\n| ridersperrow         = 4\n| virtual_queue_name   =\n| virtual_queue_image  = <!--Use ONLY the filename, not a full [[File:]] link-->\n| virtual_queue_status = <!--should be available if above fields are used-->\n| single_rider         = <!--Must be \"available\" if available.-->\n| accessible           = <!--Must be \"available\" if available.-->\n| transfer_accessible  = <!--Must be \"available\" if available.-->\n| custom_label_1       =\n| custom_value_1       =\n| custom_label_2       =\n| custom_value_2       =\n| rcdb_number          = 11437\n| video                = <!--Use ONLY the filename, not a full [[File:]] link-->\n| videosize            = <!--Must be expressed in pixels (px); default is 250px--