son\n| competition      = [[Latvian Higher League]]\n| season           = 2012\n| winners          = [[FC Daugava]]\n| relegated        = [[FB Gulbene]]\n| continentalcup1  = [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = [[FC Daugava]]\n| continentalcup2  = [[2013\u201314 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[Skonto FC|Skonto Riga]] <br> [[FK Ventspils]] <br> [[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|SK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs]]\n| continentalcup3  = [[2013\u201314 Baltic League|Baltic League]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = \n| matches          = 180\n| total goals      = 494\n| league topscorer = Mamuka Ghonghadze (18)\n| biggest home win = [[FC J\u016brmala|J\u016brmala]] 6-1 [[FC Daugava|Daugava Daugavpils]]<br/>[[Skonto FC|Skonto R\u012bga]] 5-0 [[FS METTA/Latvijas Universit\u0101te|Metta/LU]]<br/>[[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]] 5-0 [[FK Daugava (2003)|Daugava R\u012bga]]\n| biggest away win = [[FS METTA/Latvijas Universit\u0101te|Metta/LU]] 1-6 [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]<br/>[[FB Gulbene|Gulbene 2005]] 0-5 [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]<br/>[[FS METTA/Latvijas Universit\u0101te|Metta/LU]] 0-5 [[FC Daugava|Daugava Daugavpils]]\n| highest scoring  = [[FK Jelgava|Jelgava]] 3-4 [[FK Daugava (2003)|Daugava R\u012bga]]<br />[[FS METTA/Latvijas Universit\u0101te|Metta/LU]] 1-6 [[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]<br />[[FC J\u016brmala|J\u016brmala]] 6-1 [[FC Daugava|Daugava Daugavpils]]<br />[[FK Daugava (2003)|Daugava R\u012bga]] 2-5 [[FK Spartaks J\u016brmala|Spartaks]]<br />[[FK Spartaks J\u016brmala|Spartaks]] 3-4 [[FS METTA/Latvijas Universit\u0101te|Metta/LU]]\n| longest wins     = \n| longest unbeaten = \n| longest winless  = \n| longest losses   = \n| prevseason       = [[2011 Latvian Higher League|2011]]\n| nextseason       = [[2013 Latvian Higher League|2013]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2012 [[Latvian Higher League]]''' was the 21st season of top-tier [[association football|football]] in [[Latvia]]. It began on 24 March 2012 and ended on 10 November 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=2012.gada LATVIJAS FUTBOLA VIRSL\u012aGAS, SP\u0112\u013bU KALEND\u0100RS|url=http://www.lff.lv/lv/virsliga/fixtures/2012/|publisher=[[Latvian Football Federation]]|accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref>  [[FK Ventspils]] are the defending champions.\n\nThe league comprised ten teams, one more than in the previous season.\n\n==Teams==\nThe league returned to a ten-team circuit after having been forced to play the [[2011 Latvian Higher League|2011 season]] with only nine teams, following the withdrawal of [[SK Bl\u0101zma]] a few weeks before the season commenced. As a consequence of the Bl\u0101zma withdrawal, no team was directly relegated.\n\n2011 [[Latvian First League]] champions [[FS METTA/Latvijas Universit\u0101te]] from [[Riga]] were directly promoted. The team, which was founded by the METTA football school and the [[University of Latvia]] in 2007, entered the Higher League for the first time in their history.\n\n[[JFK Olimps/RFS]] finished the 2011 season in ninth place and were therefore required to compete in a two-legged promotion/relegation play-off against First Division runners-up [[FK Spartaks J\u016brmala|Spartaks J\u016brmala]]. Spartaks won the play-off 4\u20131 on aggregate and were therefore promoted to the Higher League. Similar to METTA/LU, they made their debut at the highest level of the Latvian football pyramid. Accordingly, Olimps/RFS were relegated to the First League after five seasons at the top flight.\n\n===Stadiums and locations===\n{{Location map+|Latvia|float=right|width=400|caption=Location of teams in the '''2012 Latvian Higher League'''|places=\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=57.416667|long=21.533333|label=[[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=57.1725|long=26.761111|label=[[FB Gulbene|Gulbene]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.966667|long=24.133333|label=[[FK Daugava (2003)|Daugava Riga]]<br />[[FS METTA/Latvijas Universit\u0101te|FS METTA]]<br />[[Skonto FC|Skonto]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.516667|long=21|label=[[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|Metalurgs]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.966667|long=23.75|label=[[FC J\u016brmala|J\u016brmala]]<br />[[FK Spartaks J\u016brmala|Spartaks]]|position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.58|long=23.716667|label=[[FK Jelgava|Jelgava]]|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=55.883333|long=26.533333|label=[[FC Daugava|Daugava]]|position=left}}\n}}\n\nFollowing the promotion of [[FK Spartaks J\u016brmala|FK Spartaks]], the city of [[J\u016brmala]] should have featured three clubs during the 2012 season, one more than the capital, [[Riga]], but [[FK J\u016brmala-VV]] moved to Riga, changing their name to [[FK Daugava (2003)|Daugava Riga]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Club\n! Location\n! Stadium\n! Capacity\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Daugavpils.svg|border|20px]] [[FC Daugava]]\n| [[Daugavpils]]\n| [[Daugava Stadium (Daugavpils)|Daugava Stadium]]\n| align=\"center\" | 4,100\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Riga.svg|border|20px]] [[FK Daugava (2003)|FK Daugava R\u012bga]]\n| [[Riga]]\n| [[Daugava Stadium (Riga)|Daugava Stadium]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5,000\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Gulbene.svg|border|20px]] [[FB Gulbene]]\n| [[Gulbene]]\n| [[Gulbenes Sporta Centrs]]\n| align=\"center\" | 1,500\n|-\n|[[File:Bandera Jelgava.png|border|20px]] [[FK Jelgava]]\n| [[Jelgava]]\n| [[Zemgales Olimpiskais Sporta Centrs]]\n| align=\"center\" | 2,200\n|-\n|[[File:Bandera jurmala.png|border|20px]] [[FC J\u016brmala]]\n| [[J\u016brmala]]\n| [[Slokas Stadium]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5,000\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Liep\u0101ja.svg|border|20px]] [[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|SK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs]]\n| [[Liep\u0101ja]]\n| [[Daugava Stadium (Liep\u0101ja)|Daugava Stadium]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5,083\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Riga.svg|border|20px]] [[FS METTA/Latvijas Universit\u0101te|FS Metta/LU]]\n| Riga\n| [[R\u012bgas 49. vidusskola Stadium]]\n| align=\"center\" | 250\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Riga.svg|border|20px]] [